  "prompt": "What is the temperature on the planet Mercury at the demarcation point between light and dark?",
  "response": "The temperature on Mercury at the demarcation point between the light and dark sides, often referred to as the **terminator**, can vary significantly due to the planet's lack of a substantial atmosphere to distribute heat. \n\nOn the dayside of Mercury, temperatures can soar to about **430\u00b0C (800\u00b0F)** due to intense solar radiation, while on the nightside, temperatures can plummet to around **-180\u00b0C (-290\u00b0F)** because of the lack of heat retention.\n\nAt the **terminator**, where the transition from day to night occurs, temperatures are much more moderate compared to the extremes on either side. Estimates suggest the temperature at the terminator could range from approximately **-100\u00b0C (-148\u00b0F)** to **100\u00b0C (212\u00b0F)**, depending on the exact location and time. This zone experiences rapid temperature changes as the planet rotates. \n\nMercury\u2019s slow rotation and lack of atmosphere mean these temperature gradients are extreme and localized.",
